# Documentation Standards

## Code Comments

- Explain "why", not "what" (code should be self-documenting)
- Use comments for complex business logic
- Document non-obvious decisions
- Keep comments up-to-date with code
- Remove commented-out code

## Function Documentation

- Document public APIs (parameters, return values, exceptions)
- Include usage examples for complex functions
- Document side effects
- Note performance characteristics if relevant

## File Headers (Optional)

- Include purpose/description for complex files
- Note key exports
- Include last updated date for critical files

## README Standards

- Clear project description
- Installation instructions
- Usage examples
- Configuration options
- Contributing guidelines
- License information

## API Documentation

- Document all public endpoints
- Include request/response examples
- Document error responses
- Include authentication requirements

## Documentation Maintenance

- Update docs when code changes
- Remove outdated documentation
- Keep examples working
- Sync code and docs

## Documentation Checklist

- [ ] Public APIs documented
- [ ] README is current
- [ ] Complex logic has comments
- [ ] Examples are working
- [ ] No outdated documentation
